- Movements of Lungs

Factors holding lungs AGAINST the thorax wall:
i. Surface tension holding the "visceral" and "parietal" pleura together.
ii. Intrapulmonary pressure is ALWAYS slightly greater than intrapleural pressure by 4 mm Hg .
iii. Atmospheric pressure acting on the lungs.
a) Atelectasis (collapsed lung) - hole in pleural "balloon" causes equalization of pressure and collapse of the lung.
b) Pneumothorax - abnormal air in the intrapleural space, can lead to collapsed lung.

Factors facilitating lung movement AWAY from thorax wall
i. Elasticity of lungs allows them to assume smallest shape for given pressure conditions.
ii. Fluid film on alveoli allows them to assume smallest shape for given pressure conditions.
